ce:section.ce:para:
To validate the docking procedure, a co-crystallized ligand was extracted from the principal X-ray structure of GLUT1 and re-docked to this structure using the Auto Dock program. The conformation with the highest score was selected as the index of similarity to the original X-ray structure. The RMSD value for the best result obtained from the docking and the X-ray structure was found to be 1.55 Å (Table 2
                           ). Thus, the docking procedure is able to successfully provide crystallographic conformation for cytochalasin B (CyB). This proves the notion that the crystallographic structure of GLUT1 is suitable for the design of inhibitors with great inhibitory effect on glucose uptake. The results gained from the docking model suggest that a transport pathway contains both hydrophilic and hydrophobic residues. Gln161, Gln 282, Gln 288, Asn 286, Asn 411, Glu 378, His 160, Ser 88, Trp388, Thr 137 and Trp 412 are the polar residues involved in the interaction of CyB with GLUT1(Fig. 7A and B). Furthermore, the formation of one hydrogen bond between the back-bone carbonyl group of CyB and the hydroxyl group (OH) of Thr 137 residue would stabilize the inhibitor ligand in its position. Also, hydrophobic residues such as Ile 164, Phe 26 and Ile 404 provide a stabilizing interaction with the hydrophobic benzene region of the ligand. The crystallographic conformations of CyB are proper in terms of the hydrogen bond and the hydrophobic interaction at the binding site (Fig. 9
                           A and B). Fig. 9C and D present the binding mode of RSV at the binding site of GLUT1. The residues of the binding site and its binding mode were found to be the same as those seen for CyB (Fig. 9A and B), implying that RSV can occupy the binding region of GLUT1. RSV gets stabilized by different interactions such as hydrogen bonds and hydrophobic interactions. In the docking position, six hydrogen bonds were found between RSV and the binding residues of GLUT1. In this case, the first H-bond was formed between the hydroxyl group of Thr 137 and the carbonyl group of RSV. This interaction also occurred in the co-crystal structure of GLUT1 with CyB (Fig. 9B). The carbonyl group of RSV was involved in the hydrogen bond with the side chain NH of Gln 282, Trp 388, His 160, Asn 288 and the hydroxyl group (−OH) of Gln 282 (Fig. 9D). This interaction has an important role in stabilizing the binding positions of inhibitors. In the present study, the ring of RSV facing toward the side chain of Ile 164 and Phe 26 denoted a hydrophobic interaction (Fig. 9D). This state was also present in the interaction of CyB (co-crystallized ligand) and GLUT1 (Fig. 9B). The docking studies showed that RSV has a relatively lower affinity for GLUT1 in terms of binding energy (−7.08 kcal mol−1) as compared to CyB with the binding energy of −8.85 kcal mol−1 (Table 2). CytB and RSV are located near the residues crucial for glucose transport and along with its transport channel. The binding of RSV can block this channel, thus inhibiting glucose transport.
